The core of the probabilistic engine was overhauled by transitioning the discrete probability calculations from a Tweedie-based model to a true Negative Binomial distribution, ensuring that the high-variance nature of NBA count data is accurately reflected in the predicted win rates. To further stabilize the model, a Bayesian regularization factor was integrated into the form-ratio calculations, which prevents early-season or low-sample size performances from skewing projections with extreme percentage shifts. Basketball-specific context was significantly improved through the implementation of a player-level "With or Without You" (WOWY) engine and positional pace interaction terms, allowing the model to project exact usage and scoring bumps for specific players when teammates are inactive rather than relying on generic team-level estimates. Additionally, the travel fatigue logic was modernized to utilize dynamic IANA timezone tracking, which natively accounts for Daylight Saving Time boundaries to ensure that sleep-related performance shifts are calculated with absolute accuracy. These changes collectively solve issues regarding right-tail upside underestimation, hard-coded covariance fallbacks, and timezone calculation errors, resulting in a more resilient and predictive betting infrastructure.